<br>
I worked at trying to disphyer the writing on some of the scrolls,  I had some abilities in differed languages but most of these scrolls were of an old tongue.  Frustration had set in as I sipped another glass of wine.  The room seemed to brighten as the hours past from eerily morning to daybreak.  However, I too, seemed to drift in and out as sleep was overcoming me.   My mind lost in a cloud of wine and exhaustion felt my body being lifted by strong arms, floating. Then lips warm and close to mine, breath on my cheek hands that gently brushed my body,.  Words whispered softly &quot;I love you Kat. How I want you to know that I am truly sorry that things happened the way they did.  Let me show you how much I love you&quot; then again deep sleep overtook me.<br>
  <br>
I awoke my head pounding,  I was in the bedroom I had locked myself in the night before.  The hour was late, night had come with a storm and the rain made a soft plat plat plat sound against the doors to the balcony.  I moved to the bowl of fresh water and a towels to splash my face, wash the sleep from my eyes.  I couldn't remember when I had slept so deeply without dreams.  Now all I felt was my head aching from the wine that I had had to much of.  <br>
<br>
I combed my hair and straightened my clothing before going to the door to listen for any movement on the other side. <br>
<br>
To my surprise there were voices and the sounds of many footsteps then Farvaks voice giving orders whoever was out in the hall.  I opened the door and to my surprise I was looking into the face of a familiar dark elf, one that I had seen at Farvaks house in Nektulos forest.  She was carrying fresh linen and  supplies.   <br>
<br>
Farvak said with a  growl &quot;See you have awoken the Mistress foolish girl&quot; I quickly replied  &quot;No she did no such thing&quot; as I moved between them to take his wrath off of her.  He said amusingly &quot;Kat as a Mistress you must learn to treat those beneath you with little or no value&quot;.   &quot;How dare you treat anyone as though they are beneath you! She is doing her job the very orders you gave her.&quot;  I seethed.  His grin widened as he saw my anger take flight on him &quot;OOH,  Yes that is it, You've got it now.   Just treat them like your treating me now you have it Kat&quot;   I heard her say softly behind me, &quot;it is all right mam really&quot;  She bowed and entered my room.   <br>
<br>
Farvak was leaning against the wall chuckling as he watched me.  &quot;Kat you are a beauty but when your angry you are breath taking&quot;<br>
<br>
I blushed and brushed passed him, I could feel the warmth of his body close to mine. His eyes watching my body as I passed him.  I quickly headed off towards O'Berton's study to  resume my search in the mass of books scrolls and papers.  I passed a few more servants on my way there.  Only one stopped and spoke, &quot;Mistress what may I bring you,   too too eat for dinner?&quot;   I said &quot;Just some wine, cheese and bread, thank you&quot;  I turned to enter the study as he left.   <br>
<br>
There was Salvas perched on the chair by the fire, that had been burning for some time.  I lit the lantern that was on the desk and began my chore.  &quot;So, Kat do you like what Farvak has done, does he not please you.  He is a fool in love and only wishes to make you love him, you know&quot; Salvas spoke  his eyes closed but his voice was more than awake.   &quot;That will never happen and as for you, your day is coming. Your downfall is in my future&quot; I said assuredly.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, yes the Kat who brought down the blessed Plague Bringers.  You do have a strong will to serve your Mother Tunare, but where was She and her Light bringers when Caddil was in need.  What of the Great and Mightily Bronze Dragons where was their rescue.  I do believe that it was only you Kat who did anything till the last moment.  Wasn't it you who lost it all, your family your love your child?&quot;   He said factually.  <br>
<br>
Bitterly I said &quot;It is not for you to ever speak their names, You are not to do so again!&quot;<br>
<br>
Salvas said coldly &quot;Poor Kat, she is the only one who has sacrificed and yet she doesn't see that it is she who is used by Mother Tunare and those who follow so blindly the Just and Righteous.  Farvak lives, Iszabelle is back to serve as well.  See me I have lost nothing because of your sacrifices. It is only you Kat that is the stone cold truth that has lost anything in this battle you choose to fight.  You choose the wrong side, even now!&quot;<br>
<br>
I could not say anything to refute these words, so I sat quietly.  A bitter knot in my throat and a deep stabbing pain in my heart.  I fought back the tears that dared to well up even now.  <br>
<br>
The silence was broken by the servant entering with food and drink.  He quickly placed it on the desk and left.  I poured a glass of wine and drank deep and quickly hopping to dislodge the lump in my throat. Seeing that this wasn't going to happen I turned my attention back to the scrolls and translating them.<br>
<br>
Hours must have passed, the wine was gone the food uneaten and I was more than a bit drunk.  Falling into a sleep my head on the desk.  When again I felt myself being lifted from the chair.  Warm strong arms held me, gently close to a strong muscular chest.  I nuzzled the neck of my would be hero and whispered with a slur &quot;Thank you&quot;.   Then his lips where close to mine touching them softly.   His hands  brushed lightly my thighs then my stomach, then my cheek.  Whispered words his breath against my neck &quot;Katreena you will one day love me, as I love you&quot; the voice deep and gentle with a kindness that reached into my heart. <br>
<br>
 I tried to wake up but it wasn't till very late the next day that I arose. Again the headache was blinding, my mouth dry.  Again back to the Study back to my work, Frustration  now seeping in as I was getting no where with any of it nothing about imps nothing about the dark forces.  I spent my nights working and days sleeping off the effects of a drunken wine induced sleep.  <br>
<br>
It was just when I had given up hope of finding anything that Farvak entered and spoke to Salvas I was deep in efforts to translate a very difficult document when Salvas left.  It was then that Farvak stood behind me and dropped a piece of paper in front of me.  My eyes widened as I stared at it.  I gasp as I started to read the bits I could.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, oh thank.&quot; I stated to say, then realized who I was going to thank.  &quot;What is the cost of such a bit of information, Farvak&quot; I said suspiciously.  &quot;Just the smile on your face, Kat&quot; came his reply.   He sat down in the big chair in front of the fire watching me.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Then thank you, where did you find this?&quot;  One of my servants in cleaning out an old part of the building came acrossed it. I hope that it helps&quot;  He said   <br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, and why help me destroy the very thing you worship?&quot; I replied  <br>
&quot;I have my reasons Kat&quot;  he said with almost a tone of disgust.  I did not press farther.  I was to eager to try and figure out the information that was on this small fragment of paper. <p><img border="0" src="http://www.goodnet.com/~saxon/full-logo.gif"><img border=0 src=http://bronzedragonsite.homestead.com/files/tags/katreena.gif><BR>
