<br>
 I stood up unsteadily, the cold floor giving me the reason to move quickly to the dresser.  I bathed slowly enjoying the feeling of being clean.  If only one's heart could be as easily cleansed, I thought.  There was fresh clothing laid out on the end of the bed so I stepped out of the pile at my feet and dressed.   Then picking up the soiled clothes I searched the pockets to see if I had hid the paper that Farvak had given me there.  &quot;Ah&quot; I was not so drunk to forget that little snippet of a clue.  I sat down and was surprised to find that the paper was not the one I thought.<br>
<br>
Finely written was a note that read &quot;Katreena, your very soul is endanger of being lost to Salvas. You are in need of information to help you to succeed in escaping his hold on you.  The following will help you in blocking your true thoughts from him.  I give you this to show you that I can be trussed..  You will need to know more and I can supply this if you are willing.  You need to write your answer on a paper then place it in your pocket.  I await your response.  O'Berton&quot;  <br>
<br>
There was a name that brought a shiver to my hole body and mind.  Here was another of the Plague Bringers back from the dead.  Curses filled my mind. &quot;Damn them all! Salvas was right I was the only one who had lost anything!&quot; Anger and resentment filled my head.  &quot;I had been so Foolish to believe that I mattered to any of them. Mother Tunare and her promises had been just to spur me on. Only to bring about success for her purpose.  The Bronze Dragons were they not just as guilty&quot;  I then looked into the mirror and saw my reflection there  &quot;Kat, bitterness will fill you and you will be destroyed by it&quot; I reprimanded myself. <br>
<br>
I sat on the bed staring at the note, studying the writing as if to see if there was some meaning between the words that would give me a clue as to the true intentions of the writer.  &quot;O'Berton  why would he help me now? How did he get the note into my pocket and when? Would the instructions there really keep Salvas from my mind?&quot;  I pondered these questions for a long time. &quot;Trust O'Berton?! That was like trusting Farvak!&quot;   I decided that I had nothing to lose from attempting what was given here,  then I would see about answering the note.   <br>
<br>
A knock on the door broke my study and I quickly pocketed the note as I answered. &quot;Who  is it?&quot;  Farvak's voice from beyond asked &quot;Are you okay Kat you haven't ventured to the Study today?&quot; <br>
<br>
 I answered flatly &quot;I do not have to check in with you as to my plans for the day, do I?&quot; <br>
<br>
Farvak entered &quot;Kat, stop this!&quot; <br>
<br>
 I glared at him &quot;Now you come into my room any time you choose! Remind me to lock that door from now on.&quot; I spat back.<br>
<br>
With this he backed out apologizing.  &quot;Kat, your right, I should never have entered without your bidding me to come in&quot;  <br>
<br>
This took me aback as I had never seen Farvak back down from anything or anyone.  &quot; I am,&quot; I began &quot;I'm sorry, I have a headache.&quot; I explained  &quot;Thank you for your concern. I am not fit company nor would I be able to accomplish much in the Study now.  I will try to go later&quot; I said.  I surprised myself by my sudden change of tone with Farvak. <br>
<br>
He answered through the door &quot;My I bring you something for your headache. Please let me help you&quot; it sounded like true concern. <br>
<br>
 &quot;I am not sure&quot; I replied &quot;I truly would like this pain to be gone&quot; Farvak entered asking for forgiveness for this act &quot;Kat, please let me help.  You haven't been taking care of yourself, not eating, too much wine and working to hard.  I am surprised that your not sick&quot; He approached me turning me around he started massaging my shoulders.  His hands warm and strong, yet gentle.  He moved his hands so that his fingers found my temples and lightly massaged my head.   <br>
<br>
He then spoke softly &quot;Kat you need to leave here for a time, go to a forest regain your composure and strength.  But where?&quot;  Let me talk with Salvas and see if he will not be willing to let you travel to Nektulos forest.  I believe I can convince him of that journey&quot;<br>
<br>
Again my mind was blurred and thoughts seemed to fade in and out as I agreed without realizing that I had answered.  It sounded to tempting and I did long for the green glades and meadows, tall trees and grass.  Not since Caddil had I let anyone take control of my life and I longed to be taken care of again, to let go and let someone else make the decisions.<br>
<br>
Farvak asked &quot;There now your feeling better, yes?&quot;  I was surprised to find my headache had left and answered &quot;Yes, thank you I think I will go to the Study now&quot;.  He bowed gave me a smile  &quot;Ah a pleasure to serve my Mistress&quot; then left the room.  <br>
<br>
I once again found myself in the study under Salvas's watch.  It was time to try and block him from my mind, to see if O'Berton's instructions would prove to be truth.  I started then pulled out the piece of paper Farvak had given me from under the rest of the papers there and began again to translate the writing.  I waited for Salvas to ask me about what I was reading. No response came.  I then tried to turn my thoughts to Slaor. Salvas still sat studying my actions without a reply, my blood did not boil nor did I feel any compulsion to tell Salvas anything.  <br>
<br>
It was Salvas who broke the quite of the Study and spoke &quot;Farvak says that you need to take a break from your work here and I couldn't agree more&quot;  I turned to him and looked shocked &quot;What?&quot; I asked.  I had forgotten about Farvak's plans to take me to Nektulos Forest.  &quot;Oh that&quot;I brushed it off &quot;It was just a desire nothing more than a whim I don't think I want to go now.&quot;  I waited to see if Salvas would see the rush of longing that had stirred in my mind.  Then I felt it, my blood boiled and my mind being lost to his control.  &quot;Okay, I will go then&quot; I answered frustrated by the lack of control over my own thoughts. <p><img border="0" src="http://www.goodnet.com/~saxon/full-logo.gif"><img border=0 src=http://bronzedragonsite.homestead.com/files/tags/katreena.gif><BR>
